AB  - To enhance the safety and efficiency of unmanned surface vehicle (USV) recovery operations, this study proposes a four-cable assisted positioning system (FAPS). A dynamic model of the FAPS is developed, incorporating the coupled effects of wind and wave loads, as well as inertial effects arising from vessel motion and crane actions. Given the difficulty in accurately measuring the mother vessel's attitude and the recovery cage's center of gravity, a dynamic model for disturbance decoupling is derived. To improve the positioning accuracy and attitude stability of the recovery cage, a computed torque sliding mode control with an extended state observer is developed. The recovery operation is divided into three phases: docking, berthing, and lifting. Simulation results indicate that the proposed controller effectively reduces overshoot, accelerates convergence, enhances accuracy, and lowers energy consumption. The proposed method provides theoretical and technical guidance for designing and developing USV recovery systems.
