AB  - This paper analyzes the trajectory tracking problem in decoupled planes for X-rudder AUVs under time-varying, unknown environmental interferences. The proposed scheme consists of the kinematic control law based on the compound line-of-sight guidance law and the dynamic control law based on a non-singular adaptive integral terminal sliding mode control (NAITSMC) to avoid the chattering problems, parameter perturbation, and time-varying disturbances. Meanwhile, we introduce a reduced-order extended state observer (RESO) to compensate for unknown ocean currents by the first-order Gauss-Markov process. We verify the whole system of the proposed scheme through global asymptotic stability, then present a set of numerical simulations revealing robustness and adaptability performances in decoupled planes.
